04630nam a22005655i 9780822385745DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223857457 a10.1515/97808223857452doi  a(DE-B1597)553013  a(OCoLC)1055305895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF2276 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a986.1/051 aSanders, James E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContentious Republicans :bPopular Politics, Race, and Class in Nineteenth-Century Colombia /cJames E. Sanders. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: A Social History of Politics -- t2 ''We the Undersigned, Citizens of the State'': Three Forms of Popular Republicanism -- t3 A New Politics: The Emergence of Republican Bargaining, 1848-1853 -- t4 Fragmented Hegemony: The Limits of Elite Power, 1853-1863 -- t5 The Triumph of Democracy, 1863-1876 -- t6 Failure of Discipline: The Suppression of Popular Politics, 1875-1886 -- t7 Conclusion: Popular Republicans' Legacies -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContentious Republicans explores the mid-nineteenth-century rise of mass electoral democracy in the southwestern region of Colombia, a country many assume has never had a meaningful democracy of any sort. James E. Sanders describes a surprisingly rich republicanism characterized by legal rights and popular participation, and he explains how this vibrant political culture was created largely by competing subaltern groups seeking to claim their rights as citizens and their place in the political sphere. Moving beyond the many studies of nineteenth-century nation building that focus on one segment of society, Contentious Republicans examines the political activism of three distinct social and racial groups: Afro-Colombians, Indians, and white peasant migrants.Beginning in the late 1840s, subaltern groups entered the political arena to forge alliances, both temporary and enduring, with the elite Liberal and Conservative Parties. In the process, each group formed its own political discourses and reframed republicanism to suit its distinct needs. These popular liberals and popular conservatives bargained for the parties' support and deployed a broad repertoire of political actions, including voting, demonstrations, petitions, strikes, boycotts, and armed struggle. By the 1880s, though, many wealthy Colombians of both parties blamed popular political engagement for social disorder and economic failure, and they successfully restricted lower-class participation in politics. Sanders suggests that these reactionary developments contributed to the violence and unrest afflicting modern Colombia. Yet in illuminating the country's legacy of participatory politics in the nineteenth century, he shows that the current situation is neither inevitable nor eternal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPolitical culturezColombiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical participationzColombiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aRepublicanismzColombiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial classeszColombiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385745zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385745.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c20